snippet.textDisplay:
There IS a way to save the life of an ARDS patient whose lungs are so fluid-filled that not even a ventilator can put sufficient oxygen into the bloodstream. It's called ECMO (which stands for "Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation". I estimate that of all the critical cases of COVID-19, at least 10 percent will need to be put on an ECMO machine. Unfortunately, there's an even MORE dire shortage of ECMO machines than there is a shortage of ventilators. Indeed, I believe that, between ALL American hospitals, there are less than 100 of these. Sometimes, though, not even ECMO is enough; because what can happen to some ARDS patients is that the fluid in their lungs can be colonized by bacteria such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa. Once THAT happens, then the patient will easily go into septic shock; especially if the bacteria are multi-drug resistant. In those patients, the only recourse is for doctors to do THE most heroic medical intervention I have ever read about. And here it is:

1. Perform a double pneumonectomy (surgical removal of both lungs) to rid the patient of the source of his or her septic shock. Yes, the double pneumonectomy will, within about 20 minutes, VASTLY improve the patient's condition.

2. Keep the patient on ECMO until a pair of donor lungs can be found. Yes, ECMO can be maintained indefinitely: Melissa Benoit spent six DAYS without lungs until donor lungs could be found for her.

3. Once donor lungs are found, transplant said lungs into the patient.

Here's a Wikipedia entry about ECMO: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extracorporeal_membrane_oxygenation

And here's the story about the Cystic fibrosis patient that the above radical procedure had to be used on: https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2017/01/27/they-brought-me-back-from-death-how-a-woman-survived-six-days-without-lungs/

Why are we wrecking our economies to keep sickly people from dying?

I work hard to keep healthy, as does my wife and we share our habits with our children. My wife and I don't drink alcohol or smoke cigarettes. We eat as healthy as we can and work-out regularly as well as engage in many active sports activities. As far as I've seen this virus is killing elderly who already have pre-existing conditions or younger people with pre-existing conditions. Basically it's killing the weakest people among us. Why are we not allowing that natural process to take place? Instead we are ruining our economies so that people who might be dead in another three years by other natural means get to stick around till then.

My wife and I are independent, small business owners who are out of work and there is no compensation being discussed for us in government. We are all expected to stay in our homes and do nothing so the sickly can survive this virus.

It seems to me that we love to fight against nature, even when it's not what's best for everyone.

What will be done next cold and flu season when there is still no cure and the virus is already all over the world? That's in another 7-8 months from now.

I, for one, think this is a ridiculous response to a natural effect of overpopulation and globalization. If it was killing children I'd be all for the measures taken but it's not, it's killing the old and sickly.
